@NODE "Operating mode" "Operating mode"
@SMARTWRAP
@{LINDENT 1}

@{b}Operating mode@{ub}



You can select the operating mode of DCF77 by changing the following tool types:


@{" SAFETY_LEVEL " LINK "SAFETY_LEVEL" 0}

@{" TASK_PRIORITY " LINK "TASK_PRIORITY" 0}

@{" LOCALE " LINK "LOCALE" 0}

@{" UPDATE_LOCALE " LINK "UPDATE_LOCALE" 0}

@{" DST " LINK "DST" 0}

@{" UTC " LINK "UTC" 0}

@{" GMT " LINK "UTC" 0}

@{" PAUSE " LINK "PAUSE" 0}

@{" ONE_TIME " LINK "ONE_TIME" 0}

@{" OFFSET.HOURS " LINK "OFFSETS" 0}

@{" OFFSET.MINUTES " LINK "OFFSETS" 0}

@{" OFFSET.SECONDS " LINK "OFFSETS" 0}

@{" OFFSET.MICROSECONDS " LINK "OFFSETS" 0}

@{" QUIT_AFTER_TRIALS " LINK "QUIT_AFTER_TRIALS" 0}

@{" SAVE_DST " LINK "SAVE_DST_UTC" 0}

@{" SAVE_UTC " LINK "SAVE_DST_UTC" 0}

@{" MAX_TIME_DIFFERENCE " LINK "MAX_TIME_DIFFERENCE" 0}

@{" ALLOWED_TIME_DIFFERENCE " LINK "ALLOWED_TIME_DIFFERENCE" 0}

@{" TIMER " LINK "TIMER" 0}

@{" PORT " LINK "PORT" 0}

@{" PIN " LINK "PIN" 0}

@{" PARALLEL_DEVICE_NAME " LINK "PARALLEL_DEVICE_NAME" 0}

@{" SERIAL_DEVICE_NAME " LINK "SERIAL_DEVICE_NAME" 0}

@{" UNIT " LINK "UNIT" 0}

@{" RTS " LINK "RTS" 0} 

@{" ALLOCATE_RESOURCES " LINK "ALLOCATE_RESOURCES" 0}

@{" SCAN_PORTS " LINK "SCAN_PORTS" 0}

@{" SUPPRESS_SCAN_MESSAGE " LINK "SUPPRESS_SCAN_MESSAGE" 0}

@{" SAVE_PORT " LINK "SAVE_PORT" 0}

@{" CONTROL_GAMEPORT_HARDWARE " LINK "CONTROL_GAMEPORT_HARDWARE" 0}

@{" CONTROL_PARALLEL_HARDWARE " LINK "CONTROL_PARALLEL_HARDWARE" 0}

@{" CONTROL_SERIAL_HARDWARE " LINK "CONTROL_SERIAL_HARDWARE" 0}

@{" SCAN_RATE " LINK "SCAN_RATE" 0}



@ENDNODE

@NODE "SAFETY_LEVEL" "SAFETY_LEVEL"
@SMARTWRAP
@{LINDENT 2}

@{b}SAFETY_LEVEL@{ub}              Default:  SAFETY_LEVEL=1


DCF77 accepts the transmitted information only if the time of repeated receivings
is identical.


SAFETY_LEVEL controls the number of repetitions.



@ENDNODE

@NODE "TASK_PRIORITY" "TASK_PRIORITY"
@SMARTWRAP
@{LINDENT 2}

@{b}TASK_PRIORITY@{ub}             Default:  TASK_PRIORITY=0


Selects the task priority of DCF77.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "LOCALE" "LOCALE"
@SMARTWRAP
@{LINDENT 2}

@{b}LOCALE@{ub}                    Default:  LOCALE=YES


YES: Use time zone of the locale library.
If you need a special time zone, it may be necessary to disable the Daylight
Saving Time  @{" DST " LINK "DST" 0}.


NO:  Use MET.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "UPDATE_LOCALE" "UPDATE_LOCALE"
@SMARTWRAP
@{LINDENT 2}

@{b}UPDATE_LOCALE@{ub}             Default:  UPDATE_LOCALE=YES


YES: Read time zone before setting system time.


NO:  Read time zone only one time.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "DST" "DST"
@SMARTWRAP
@{LINDENT 2}

@{b}DST@{ub}                       Default:  DST=YES

                          (DST - Daylight Saving Time)


YES: Use the chosen time zone with DST while MEST (Middle European Summer Time).


NO:  Use the chosen time zone without DST.




@ENDNODE

@NODE "UTC" "UTC"
@SMARTWRAP
@{LINDENT 2}

@{b}UTC@{ub}                       Default:  UTC=NO

                          (UTC - Universal Time Coordinated)


YES: Use UTC.


This is the same like

  LOCALE=NO

  DST=NO

  OFFSET.HOURS=-1


If UTC=YES then DCF77 ignores @{" LOCALE " LINK "LOCALE" 0} and @{" DST " LINK "DST" 0},
but the @{" offsets " LINK "OFFSETS" 0} are used.


NO: Use the chosen time zone.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "PAUSE" "PAUSE"
@SMARTWRAP
@{LINDENT 2}

@{b}PAUSE@{ub}                     Default:  PAUSE=0


Sleep some time (in seconds) after setting the system time.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "ONE_TIME" "ONE_TIME"
@SMARTWRAP
@{LINDENT 2}

@{b}ONE_TIME@{ub}                  Default:  ONE_TIME=NO


YES: Set system time only one time.


NO:  Run continuously.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "OFFSETS" "OFFSETS"
@SMARTWRAP
@{lindent 2}

@{b}OFFSET.HOURS@{ub}              Default:  OFFSET.HOURS=0

@{b}OFFSET.MINUTES@{ub}                      OFFSET.MINUTES=0

@{b}OFFSET.SECONDS@{ub}                      OFFSET.SECONDS=0

@{b}OFFSET.MICROSECONDS@{ub}                 OFFSET.MICROSECONDS=0


The offsets are added to the received time.


This works for ±68 years if the result is in the range of the Amiga system time:

@{lindent 4}

to   Amiga-OS 2.1   1.1.1978 00:00:00  -  19. 1.2046 03:14:08

from Amiga-OS 3.0   1.1.1978 00:00:00  -  31.12.2099 23:59:59.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "QUIT_AFTER_TRIALS" "QUIT_AFTER_TRIALS"
@SMARTWRAP
@{LINDENT 2}

@{b}QUIT_AFTER_TRIALS@{ub}         Default:  QUIT_AFTER_TRIALS=0


If you enter zero, then DCF77 runs continuously.


If you enter any other value, then DCF77 makes the given number of trials to receive
and afterwards it quits if the receiving was not successful.

The internal timeout is about 2 seconds. So you can use QUIT_AFTER_TRIALS=90
to stop DCF77 after 3 minutes of work without a receiver.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "SAVE_DST_UTC" "SAVE_DST, SAVE_UTC"
@SMARTWRAP
@{LINDENT 2}

@{b}SAVE_DST@{ub}                  Default:  SAVE_DST=YES

@{b}SAVE_UTC@{ub}                  Default:  SAVE_UTC=NO


These tool types are for future compatibility:

You may need one of it, if a new Amiga operating system supports daylight
saving time.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "MAX_TIME_DIFFERENCE" "MAX_TIME_DIFFERENCE"
@SMARTWRAP
@{LINDENT 2}

@{b}MAX_TIME_DIFFERENCE@{ub}       Default:  MAX_TIME_DIFFERENCE=1


Maximum difference between system time and time of battery backed up clock.


Only needed for Amigas with bad clock chip.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "ALLOWED_TIME_DIFFERENCE" "ALLOWED_TIME_DIFFERENCE"
@SMARTWRAP
@{LINDENT 2}

@{b}ALLOWED_TIME_DIFFERENCE@{ub}   Default:  ALLOWED_TIME_DIFFERENCE=0


DCF77 sets the system time only if the difference between the radio clock
and the system time is greater than this value (in microseconds).

@ENDNODE

@NODE "TIMER" "TIMER"
@SMARTWRAP
@{LINDENT 2}

@{b}TIMER@{ub}                     Default:  TIMER=GAMEPORT_DEVICE


Selects DCF77 timer for gameport 2, pin 6.

You can use

TIMER=GAMEPORT_DEVICE or

TIMER=TIMER_DEVICE.


Try timer device if you have compatibility problems with other gameport hardware.

In timer device mode DCF77 consumes much more processor time and you should
increase the @{" TASK_PRIORITY " LINK "TASK_PRIORITY" 0}.


If @{" PORT " LINK "PORT" 0} and @{" PIN " LINK "PIN" 0} specifies not gameport 2,
pin 6 then DCF77 works always with the timer device.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "PORT" "PORT"
@SMARTWRAP
@{LINDENT 2}

@{b}PORT@{ub}                      Default:  PORT=GAMEPORT_2


Selects port for DCF77 receiver.


Current choices are

PORT=GAMEPORT_1

PORT=GAMEPORT_2

PORT=PARALLEL

PORT=SERIAL

PORT=PARALLEL_DEVICE

PORT=SERIAL_DEVICE


Use @{" PIN " LINK "PIN" 0} to select the pin for the receiver signal.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "PIN" "PIN"
@SMARTWRAP
@{LINDENT 2}

@{b}PIN@{ub}                       Default:  PIN=6  (for PORT=GAMEPORT_2)

                                    PIN=5  (for PORT=GAMEPORT_1)

                                    PIN=3  (for PORT=SERIAL)

                                    PIN=2  (for PORT=PARALLEL)

                                    PIN=11 (for PORT=PARALLEL_DEVICE)

                                    PIN=8  (for PORT=SERIAL_DEVICE)


Selects the pin for the receiver signal of the port selected with
@{" PORT " LINK "PORT" 0}.


Choices are:

if PORT=GAMEPORT_1 then you can use pin 5,

if PORT=GAMEPORT_2 then you can use the pins 1 to 6 or 9,

if PORT=SERIAL then you can use the pins 3 or 8,

if PORT=PARALLEL then you can use the pins 2 to 9 or 11,

if PORT=PARALLEL_DEVICE then you can use pin 11,

if PORT=SERIAL_DEVICE then you can use pin 8.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "PARALLEL_DEVICE_NAME" "PARALLEL_DEVICE_NAME"
@SMARTWRAP
@{LINDENT 2}

@{b}PARALLEL_DEVICE_NAME@{ub}      Default:  PARALLEL_DEVICE_NAME=parallel.device


Selects the device for PORT=PARALLEL_DEVICE.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "SERIAL_DEVICE_NAME" "SERIAL_DEVICE_NAME"
@SMARTWRAP
@{LINDENT 2}

@{b}SERIAL_DEVICE_NAME@{ub}        Default:  SERIAL_DEVICE_NAME=serial.device


Selects the device for PORT=SERIAL_DEVICE.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "UNIT" "UNIT"
@SMARTWRAP
@{LINDENT 2}

@{b}UNIT@{ub}                      Default:  UNIT=0


Unit number for
PORT=PARALLEL_DEVICE or PORT=SERIAL_DEVICE.

@ENDNODE



@NODE "RTS" "RTS"
@SMARTWRAP
@{LINDENT 2}

@{b}RTS@{ub}                       Default:  RTS=HIGH


Polarity of the power supply in mode PORT=SERIAL and PIN=3.

RTS=HIGH:  RTS - Plus,  DTR - Minus

RTS=LOW:   DTR - Plus,  RTS - Minus.



@ENDNODE


@NODE "ALLOCATE_RESOURCES" "ALLOCATE_RESOURCES"
@SMARTWRAP
@{LINDENT 2}

@{b}ALLOCATE_RESOURCES@{ub}        Default:  ALLOCATE_RESOURCES=YES



YES: Allocate selected @{" PORT " LINK "PORT" 0}.


NO:  Do not allocate selected @{" PORT " LINK "PORT" 0}. This operating mode
does not comply with the developer guidelines. Use it only if absolutely
necessary.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "SCAN_PORTS" "SCAN_PORTS"
@SMARTWRAP
@{LINDENT 2}

@{b}SCAN_PORTS@{ub}                Default:  SCAN_PORTS=YES


YES: Scan all supported Ports for the DCF77 receiver.


NO:  DCF77 expects the receiver on the port selected
with @{" PORT " LINK "PORT" 0} und @{" PIN " LINK "PIN" 0}.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "SUPPRESS_SCAN_MESSAGE" "SUPPRESS_SCAN_MESSAGE"
@SMARTWRAP
@{LINDENT 2}

@{b}SUPPRESS_SCAN_MESSAGE@{ub}     Default:  SUPPRESS_SCAN_MESSAGE=NO


YES: DCF77 will inform you of allocated ports while scanning the ports for the
radio clock receiver.


NO:  DCF77 will not report allocated ports while scanning.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "SAVE_PORT" "SAVE_PORT"
@SMARTWRAP
@{LINDENT 2}

@{b}SAVE_PORT@{ub}                 Default:  SAVE_PORT=YES


YES: DCF77 saves the port searched with the SCAN_PORT function
into the tool types after the first successful receiving of the time,
and it sets @{" SCAN_PORTS " LINK "SCAN_PORTS" 0} to NO.

So DCF77 searches only one time for the receiver and knows port and pin
the next time.

Later, if you would change the port used by the receiver, you have to set
SCAN_PORTS to YES.


NO: The tool types will be not changed.



@ENDNODE

@NODE "CONTROL_GAMEPORT_HARDWARE" "CONTROL_GAMEPORT_HARDWARE"
@SMARTWRAP
@{LINDENT 2}

@{b}CONTROL_GAMEPORT_HARDWARE@{ub}          Default:  CONTROL_GAMEPORT_HARDWARE=NO


YES: DCF77 writes to the control register of the gameport (POTGO)
for gameport 2, pin 5 or 9 and timer device mode. Only the current bit is affected.


NO: DCF77 changes no registers. It may work in the most cases, because the operating
system sets the ports to input.
This may be useful to avoid conflicts, if the gameport is shared with other programs.


The default is NO to avoid this effect: The writing to the POTGO register causes an
interrupt and the gameport device will interpret it as click of the right mouse
button.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "CONTROL_PARALLEL_HARDWARE" "CONTROL_PARALLEL_HARDWARE"
@SMARTWRAP
@{LINDENT 2}

@{b}CONTROL_PARALLEL_HARDWARE@{ub}          Default:  CONTROL_PARALLEL_HARDWARE=YES


YES: DCF77 sets the control registers of the parallel port to input. Only the
current bit is affected.


NO: DCF77 do not change the registers. Because the data bits of the parallel port 
are set to output by the operating system, DCF77 can only work, if you control the
port by an other program.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "CONTROL_SERIAL_HARDWARE" "CONTROL_SERIAL_HARDWARE"
@SMARTWRAP
@{LINDENT 2}

@{b}CONTROL_SERIAL_HARDWARE@{ub}          Default:  CONTROL_SERIAL_HARDWARE=YES


YES: DCF77 writes to the control registers of the actual port:

For the serial port, pin 3 (RxD) the power supply for the receiver via RTS and DTR
is activated.

For the gameport 2, pins 5 or 9 and timer device the entire control register (POTGO)
is set to input.


NO: DCF77 changes no registers.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "SCAN_RATE" "SCAN_RATE"
@SMARTWRAP
@{LINDENT 2}

@{b}SCAN_RATE@{ub}                 Default:  SCAN_RATE=23


Minimum:  1
Maximum: 40



@ENDNODE

